# Python Sudoku

A playable Python/Flask Sudoku prototype built as a reference implementation for future browser-game work.

This project was created to prove the core Sudoku logic, validation, and gameplay flow before building a more polished JavaScript version for another project, such as EddiesGames.xyz.

## Project Status

This repo is considered a completed Python prototype.

The current version is playable in the browser and includes the main gameplay systems needed for a Sudoku game. Further polish, mobile-first layout work, leaderboard integration, sharing, and production game styling are planned for the later JavaScript/browser-game version rather than this Python prototype.

A mobile version is planned conceptually, but it is not actively being worked on in this repo. The Python version has served its purpose as a working concept and reference build.

## Features

- Flask web app
- Random solved Sudoku board generation
- Unique-solution puzzle generation
- Easy, Medium, and Hard difficulty settings
- Solver-based solution validation
- Browser-rendered Sudoku board
- Player input with answer-key validation
- Notes / pencil marks
- Timer
- Move count
- Pause mode
- Board hidden during pause
- Light and dark mode
- Row, column, box, and matching-number highlighting
- Completed-number indicators
- New Puzzle button
- Show Solution developer option
- Test Solution developer option
- Completion detection and win message
- Automated pytest coverage
- Batch board generation and validation script

## Difficulty Settings

The current difficulty levels use visible clue counts:

- Easy: 40 visible clues
- Medium: 35 visible clues
- Hard: 32 visible clues

These values were tested during development using batch board generation. The generator successfully produced unique-solution puzzles at the current Hard setting across 1,000-board validation runs.

Difficulty in this prototype is clue-count based. Future versions may use more advanced difficulty scoring based on solving techniques.

## Testing

The project includes pytest coverage for:

- Valid solved board generation
- Invalid board rejection
- Puzzle creation
- Unique puzzle generation
- Solver behavior
- Difficulty configuration
- API solution testing

The solver can detect:

- No solution
- One unique solution
- Multiple solutions

Run tests with:

    pytest -v

## Batch Testing

The repo includes a batch testing script for generating and validating many puzzles.

Example:

    python scripts/batch_test_boards.py --boards 1000 --visible 32 --max-attempts 1000

The script reports:

- Requested board count
- Visible clue count
- Successful boards
- Failed boards
- Total run time
- Average time per board
- Slowest board time

This was used to stress-test the generator and confirm that the current clue counts are reliable for this prototype.

